install apache2.
Code

    sudo apt install apache2

Confirm the installation when prompted. Adjust the Firewall (UFW).
If you are using UFW (Uncomplicated Firewall), you need to allow Apache traffic. First, list the available Apache profiles:
Code

    sudo ufw app list

sudo ufw allow 'Apache Full'

sudo systemctl status apache2

    sudo nano /etc/apache2/apache2.conf

 ServerName localhost

sudo apt install postgresql postgresql-contrib

The PostgreSQL server typically starts automatically after installation. 
3. Verify Installation (Optional) To check if PostgreSQL is running, you can use the following command: 
Code

sudo systemctl status postgresql

4. Connect to the PostgreSQL Server You can connect to the PostgreSQL command-line client (psql) as the postgres superuser using this command: 
Code

sudo -u postgres psql

5. Set a Password for the postgres User Once inside the psql shell, set a strong password for the default postgres user to improve security: 
Code

ALTER USER postgres PASSWORD 'killy';

Code

    sudo -i -u postgres

Access the PostgreSQL prompt (psql).
Code

    psql

Create the new database.
Replace your_database_name with the desired name for your database.
Code

    CREATE DATABASE your_database_name;

Verify the database creation (optional).
This command lists all databases on the server.
Code

    \l

Exit the PostgreSQL prompt.
Code

    \q

Return to your regular user account.
Code

    exit

Alternatively, you can use the createdb command-line utility directly from your regular user account (assuming you have the necessary permissions, or run with sudo if needed and configured).
Code

sudo -u postgres createdb your_database_name

